<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-07-26T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-07-26T18:00:00-05:00" n="307" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d307">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">882.5048/52: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Wharton</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-07-26T19:00:00-04:00">July 26, 1929—7
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>28. Your confidential telegram July 24, 10 p.m. Last paragraph.
                            Department would regard in a most serious light the export of laborers
                            at this time when the whole question of the export of labor is about to
                            be made the subject of an investigation. You may so advise President <pb facs="0410" n="292" xml:id="pg_292"/> King informally suggesting the
                            advisability of taking steps to prevent any shipments.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>